deck: He was a counselor at Camp Crystal Lake in the first Friday the 13th film. He was one of Kevin Bacon's earliest roles.
description:
Biography (Film)

Jack Marand was a counselor at Camp Crystal Lake together with his girlfriend Marcie and friend Ned Rubinstein. He enjoyed smoking weed and listening to the rain. Marcie was plagued by dreams of raining blood, which Jack ignored. He lay down to rest for a minute, only to have his head jerked back as an arrow was forced out from under the bed and right through his neck. Blood spurted everywhere. Jack had been murdered by Pamela Voorhees.

Jack was portrayed by actor Kevin Bacon shortly before he became famous for other roles. Jack's death is generally considered the most gruesome in the film by fans of the series.

Comics

In Wildstorm's Freddy Vs Jason Vs Ash, Freddy tries to kill off Jason by summoning up all "Voorhees victims past and present" as Deadites. Jack is one of the few recognizable ones from the films. Whether this is truly Jack or simply a demon is unknown since he recognizes Jason even though he was killed by Jason's mother Pamela.
name: Jack Marand

volume_credits.name: Freddy vs Jason vs Ash (of Army of Darkness)

deck: He was a practical joker who Jason Voorhees ended up taking his hockey mask from.
description:
Biography (Film)

Friday the 13th Part 3

Sheldon "Shelly" P. Finkelstein was a wannabe actor who accompanied his friend Andy to Higgins Haven for a weekend get together with some friends. Shelly was self-conscious about his looks and preferred to wear various odd masks. Andy set him up on a blind date with a girl named Vera, who found him bizarre. Scared of being rejected or considered boring, Shelly delighted in playing gruesome pranks on his friends such as faking his own death and leaping out at them while wearing masks.

Trying to prove he wasn't a bad guy, Shelly drove Vera out to a convenience store to buy groceries, but ended up in a confrontation with a biker gang, who followed them back to Higgins Haven. Unbeknownst to all involved, Jason Voorhees had taken up residence in the barn, and this resulted in Jason killing off first the bikers, and then everyone at the ranch.

Vera was beginning to warm up to Shelly, if not romantically, but he ruined this growing friendship by leaping out at the water while wearing a hockey mask and scuba gear. This would be the last prank he would ever pull. Jason Voorhees took a liking to the mask and slit Shelly's throat. Shelly tried to get help, but his pleas were ignored because of all the pranks he had pulled. He then bled to death, unknowingly having given his murderer a "face" that would become iconic.

Comics

In Freddy Vs Jason Vs Ash, Freddy uses the Necronomicon to summon up all "Voorhees victims past and present" in order to dispose of Jason. Shelly is among the vengeful horde, first in silhouette but recognizable because of his hair. He is not wearing his scuba gear that he died in, suggesting this is not the real Shelly.
name: Shelly Finkelstein

volume_credits.name: Freddy vs Jason vs Ash (of Army of Darkness)

deck: He was the comic relief character in Friday the 13th: The Final Chapter. Played by Crispin Glover.
description:
Biography

Jimmy "Jimbo" was a social misfit with no real friends except for his condescending frat house brother Ted, who teased him for striking out with a girl named "Blow-Job Betty" because Jimmy had erectile dysfunction. Ted delighted in calling him "Dead Fuck". The two accompanied some other frat house brothers to Crystal Lake for a weekend, where they rented a house belonging to Tommy Jarvis's mother. Jimmy was determined to get laid, and resorted to desperate measures such as a truly embarrassing attempt at break-dancing to some heavy metal music.

One of the girls took pity on Jimbo and he succeeded at getting laid. Jimbo went to celebrate with wine, but had no idea that Jason Voorhees had gotten in the house. Jimmy asked for a corkscrew, and ended up getting it...right in his hand. A meat cleaver to the face then finished him off.

Comics

In Freddy Vs Jason Vs Ash, Freddy summons up several of Jason's murder victims to dispose of the hulking brute. Jimbo is the most instantly identifiable among them because of the cleaver in his face.

The corkscrew is still visibly stuck in his hand.
name: Jimbo

volume_credits.name: Freddy vs Jason vs Ash (of Army of Darkness)

deck: Eddie was a victim of Roy Burns in Friday the 13th 5: A New Beginning. He made a bizarre cameo in 'Freddy Vs Jason Vs Ash'
description:
Biography

Eddie (last name unrevealed) was an inmate at Pinehurst Sanitarium for Juvenile Delinquents. It is unknown what he was imprisoned for. Eddie took delight in playing pranks and sneaking out to have sex with his girlfriend, which put him at odds with the locals. He also ended up receiving a brutal beating from Tommy Jarvis after stealing one of Tommy's monster masks.

Eddie was slain by Roy Burns, the Jason impostor who was targeting inmates at Pinehurst after one had murdered his son. Roy killed him by having his belt tied around his head and twisted until it caved in his eyeballs.

Comics

In Freddy Vs Jason Vs Ash, Freddy uses the Necronomicon to summon up "All Voorhees victims past and present" as Deadites to dispose of Jason. Eddie is among them and seemingly possesses the most strength and gets the most panel time.

This appearance is a continuity disaster, as Eddie was killed by neither Jason Voorhees or his mother Pamela. It is possible that the "Jason Victim" Deadites were actually demons and not the people they appeared to be. Another possibility is that Burns was possessed by Jason.
name: Eddie

deck: A Xenomorph born from Fahrenheit of Stormwatch, thus granting it the power to breathe fire rather than spit acid.
description:
Creation

The Fire-Eater Alien was created by Warren Ellis and Chris Sprouse. It made a singular appearance in the 1998 crossover one-shot, WildC.A.T.s/Aliens.

Major Story Arc

WildC.A.T.s/Aliens

After Skywatch was attacked by an unidentified alien threat, a newly-reassembled WildC.A.T.s team set out to combat what they believed to be a Daemonite threat. They were instead met by the entirely unanticipated threat of Xenomorphs, which had invaded Skywatch, and used many of its personnel to create more of its warriors.

While searching Skywatch for survivors, the WildC.A.T.s team was surprised yet elated to come across Fahrenheit. They soon saw that it was actually just her lifeless body being carried by the Fire-Eater Xenomorph that had burst from her chest. It then further surprised the WildC.A.T.s team by releasing a massive burst of fire from its mouth. This caused Spartan and Grifter to realize just how grave a threat the Xenomorphs could prove to be given the number of superhumans aboard the Skywatch space-station for the aliens to use as hosts.

The Fire-Eater Alien was killed along with its Xenomorph kin when Winter piloted Skywatch into the sun in order to prevent the Xenomorph threat from reaching Earth. The WildC.A.T.s survived thanks to the teleportation abilities of Void.

Powers & Abilities

The Fire-Eater Alien had the traits inherent in all Xenomorphs - claws, acid blood, and so forth; it also possessed the unique ability to breathe fire because of Fahrenheit having been its host, but it did not appear to have access to Fahrenheit's full abilities to project and control fire.
name: Fire-Eater Alien

deck: A massive Xenomorph spawned from a crocodile host. Featured in a Batman/Aliens crossover.
description:
Creation

The Crocodile Alien was an enormous Xenomorph created by writer Ron Marz and famed horror comics artist Bernie Wrightson. It made a singular appearance in the second issue of the 1997 two-part Batman/Aliens crossover comic.

Major Story Arc

Batman/Aliens

After Wayne Tech lost contact with archeologist Abel Barrett in the Amazon Jungle, Batman stepped in to discover the reason for his disappearance. Together with a five-person government special forces team known as Deadman's Hand that had been hired to investigate a site near where Barrett had disappeared, Batman found Barrett's body in a crashed alien spaceship, having died after being used as a host body for one the Xenomorph Warriors they came across at the site. Based on the number of human and alien corpses present and the nature of their deaths, Batman deduced that only three of these alien warriors were present, with one being killed in a suicide explosion by one of the Dead Man's Hand. Batman had no way of knowing of the crocodile however that unwittingly stumbled across a Xenomorph egg in a cavern and became impregnated by a Xenomorph Facehugger.

After Dead Man's Hand were cut down to only two members by the alien warriors, they and Batman came across an ancient Mayan structure hidden in an underground cavern - a structure Batman presumed based on hieroglyphics that had been used for ritual sacrifices in the past. As Batman and the two survivors tried to make it out of the cavern and escape the Xenomorphs, the aliens tracked them down. One wound up being destroyed with an explosive device by Batman, while the other was placated when Hyatt of the Dead Man's Hand let it take her only remaining partner. She then double-crossed Batman when the way out was in sight so that she would be the only survivor and receive all the recognition for the discovery of the Xenomorphs, which she intended to be sold as bio-weapons. As she was about to shoot Batman however, the Xenomorph that hatched from the crocodile appeared and brutally killed her. The Crocodile Alien then set its sights on Batman and pursued him up the steps of the Mayan sacrificial structure. Batman was at most able to make some superficial wounds on the massive alien, but its acid blood melted through the Mayan structure, revealing to Batman that it was built on top of a lava pit. Making the creature bleed enough for its acid blood to wear away the floor of the Mayan structure, Batman swung away on a Batarang cable as the Crocodile Alien fell into the lava pit and burned away in the molten rock.

Powers & Abilities

The Crocodile Alien presumably possessed all the characteristic traits of Xenomorphs, albeit on a much larger scale. It was fast, agile, had razor-sharp claws, fangs, a long prehensile tongue with fangs, and acidic blood. Its size made it undoubtedly much stronger and more durable than the average Xenomorph, and it possessed remnants of scales from its host - most likely adding to its durability.
name: Crocodile Alien

deck: For countless millennia, The Celestial Gardener tended to the "evolutionary garden" more commonly known as Earth. He was recently assassinated by Uriel Worthington, causing a major shift in the balance of power in the Marvel Universe.
description:
A Simple Gardener

The Celestial Gardener is a near-identical twin of Arishem the Judge who was tasked with tending to the "evolutionary garden" called Earth.

Years after the death of their first Earth-born Caretaker, the mutant tyrant known as Apocalypse, he was on the far side of the black matter nucleus that protects our universe when he received a Caretaker signal coming all the way from a Starcore Station orbiting the Sun.

After effortlessly leaping over to the station, he confronted Genocide, the son of Apocalypse, who was more than prepared to take his father's place as Caretaker. After some consideration, the Gardener found him worthy of the role and gave Genocide a Celestial Death Seed.

But before the Gardener could equip him with the standard issue armor given to all Caretaker's upon the completion of their initiation they were attacked by the Apocalypse Twins: Uriel and Eimin Worthington, the children of Archangel and Ichisumi.

Using Thor's axe, Jarnbjorn, Uriel split the Celestial Gardener in half and killed him causing a massive disturbance in the natural order of the cosmos.

As the Gardener died, the curiosity he had originally felt towards the twins turned to sadness, sadness for the life it had tended for so long and for those who would suffer the consequences of their actions.

Alternate Realities

Age of Apocalypse (Earth-295)

On Earth-295, a different Celestial Gardener had been assigned to tend to Earth, which it did up until it was murdered by an unknown force.

The Gardener's armor remained sprawled out on top of the more forested regions of the Savage Land where plants had already begun to grow on its surface.

The X-Force of Earth-616 along with Dark Beast entered the armor in order to find a Celestial Life Seed that could reverse Archangel's transformation into the next Apocalypse, after a fierce battle with several drones that looked identical to the dead Gardener's colleagues, X-Force managed to escape from the body with the Life Seed.

The corpse of the Gardener was eventually destroyed along with the rest of Earth-295 during a Multiverse-wide crisis.

deck: Plus Ultra, a.k.a. Kristen Kounslar, is a professional superhero who moonlights as an actress in her civilian life.
description:
When Kristen was just into her early 20s, her acting career was not moving in the direction that she wanted. She was frustrated by losing parts to sexier actresses. On a whim, Kristen visited Hero Corp for a treatment, and won the lottery of super powers, gaining most of the "alpha set". Plus Ultra possesses superhuman strength, speed, and stamina, and is nearly invulnerable.

After gaining her super powers, Kristen remembered having been slighted in her acting career because of her lack of sex appeal. Knowing that being a professional hero meant the potential for lucrative endorsement deals, Kristen decided to develop a persona that was more marketable. The result was Plus Ultra. Kristen put on some heels, a blond wig, blue contacts, and stuffed her bra as big as she could, then stepped out into the public eye, soon becoming the city's most celebrated hero .
name: Plus Ultra

deck: An Overground Comics' original character, Insight, who can be seen in issue #1 of Absent Captain.
description: Jennifer Judge grew up in Summit City, the daughter of a police detective. She was fascinated by crime investigation from an early age, and showed a tremendous aptitude for recognizing details and patterns. Despite her father's protests, after college Jennifer sought work as a registered hero at Zero Technologies. Jennifer was accepted into the organization and given a spot on their flagship team, the Cavaliers, and given the code name "Insight". Given her natural abilities, technicians developed for her a pair of goggles with lenses that give her the ability to see things unnoticeable to the naked eye. These lenses, combined with Jennifer's natural gifts make it nearly impossible for any relevant details to escape her notice. In her civilian identity, Jennifer is a board member at Zero Technologies, which is known only to Captain Zero, her team leader and mentor. Her role on the board is to constantly protect the interests of the team so that they don't suffer for the gains of the corporation.
name: Insight

deck: Major Impact is a member of Captain Zero's Cavaliers
description: James Henry Kennedy spent his youth in the military, and when his tour was over, he sought out new adventures across the world. After a few years abroad, he found that he had a younger half brother that he had never met. His mother had remarried after the death of his father, but he didn't know since his mother had cut all ties with the family. His half brother, Jonathan Argos, told him about his dreams to one day become a superhero, and expressed his frustrations about having not responded to treatment from Herocorp. James suggested using some of his inherited fortune to help Jonathan start his own company. Jonathan was a technological genius, and with his half brothers investment he started a new company called Zero Technologies, named after a prototype suit he was working on that would give him the ability to defy gravity. After mastering his own suit, Jonathan convinced James to try one of his own, and soon created for him a suit that gave him the ability to manipulate inertia. In the suit, James ironically goes by the name of Major Impact, and when he is near the Zero Technologies central wireless battery, he is nearly unstoppable.
name: Major Impact

deck: Megalith is a member of Captain Zero's Cavaliers.
description:
Megalith is the most mysterious member of the Cavaliers, but is also the glue that holds the team together. An American of Iranian descent, Megalith has struggled through bigotry and judgment for most of his life, and he focuses himself on overcoming his anger about it through personal discipline. An immense man of great natural strength, Megalith came to Zero Technologies to break barriers racially and represent his culture in the superhero community. Megalith chose Zero Technologies over Herocorp because he didn't want to unnaturally augment his body, but he wanted to be strong enough to fight for those like him who are looked down upon by many.

Megalith was fitted with a suit that contains samples of all existing pure solid elements, and a genetic synthesizer that allows his body to become a living alloy of whatever element he chooses. This can make Megalith nearly indestructible, and gives him superhuman strength.
name: Megalith

deck: Kendall Kirby, as Pulser, is a member of Captain Zero's Cavaliers.
description:
Kendall Kirby is a world class gymnast who competed for her country when she was only 16 years old. Kendall surprised her team and coaches, quickly moving up from a reserve to a favorite to medal in the Olympic games. Unfortunately, in a preliminary round Kendall suffered a knee injury that kept her out of the rest of the competition. Lighthearted an spirited, Kendall wasn't devastated by the injury. Once she turned 18, Kendall applied for a position as a hero at Zero Technologies. Despite her youth, her athletic background and favor in the public eye persuaded the company to bring her aboard.

Kendall was fitted with a special pair of gauntlets that emit a bio-magnetic pulse that can disrupt the physiology of any living person, rendering them unconscious. Kendall chose the codename Pulser, and once her combat training was complete, she was added to Captain Zero's Cavaliers, become their youngest member ever.
name: Pulser

deck: Rhapsody is a member of Captain Zero's Cavaliers.  She is possessed by the spirit of a powerful ancient witch, but is able to control the possessing spirit with the help of an inhibitor collar.
description: Not much is known about Rhapsody's past, but it is assumed that she became a part of Captain Zero's Cavaliers because of a supposed romantic involvement with Captain Zero. Rhapsody has no super powers, but when she is in control of the spirit that possesses her, she is very powerful. It has been theorized that the spirit that possesses Rhapsody is that of an ancient super powered woman who was accused of witchcraft, but in today's world may have been regarded as a superhero. Rhapsody is also known to be constantly decorated with Christian symbolism, despite it being apparently contrary to her outward nature.
name: Rhapsody

deck: Natalie Worthy is an arrogant, careless, irresponsible and selfish young woman, who just happens to be invincible.
description:
Natalie Worthy discovered when she was a teenager that she had apparently become invulnerable. Natalie didn't react to her "super powers" in a very typical fashion. She kept them a secret from others because she didn't want to accept the responsibilities or attention that would likely be expected of her if people knew what she was capable of. Instead, Natalie chose to use her powers to play pranks and get a rise out of people. Over time, Natalie's condition began to affect her life more deeply than she expected. Her invulnerability began to cause her to disconnect with her feelings and emotions. She became obsessed with pushing the boundaries of her power, and sought out grander ways of testing herself, eventually stepping off of a building, just to see if she could survive.

Natalie realized during the fall that she valued her life more than she remembered, but was arrested for the damage and disturbance caused from what she had done. Fortunately, Natalie was called before a judge who was particularly interested in superheroes, and was curious about Natalie's lack of desire to be one, despite her powers. He offered her the opportunity to avoid jail time by attending a new school he had helped establish for young super powered individuals who wanted to become professional heroes. Natalie accepted, only because she preferred nearly anything over jail time.

Natalie was able to coast through and graduate the program, but only because the school's staff had been asked to ensure that no students from their first class failed, due to the negative publicity it would cause them. Natalie made no friends at the school, and intended to disappear into obscurity once she graduated. Her graduating class was put on a plane to be flown out to an elaborate, televised ceremony, but the plane would not reach it's destination. The plane was attacked over the desert in west Texas by an unknown villain who had the ability to appear as organic electricity. The villain killed every student on the plane and destroyed it, but was unable to harm Natalie. Having survived the crash, Natalie decided that while she didn't care for being a hero, she didn't appreciate the attempt on her life, and resolved to find the villain and bring him to justice. Whether or not she has the conviction to do so remains to be seen.
name: Natalie Worthy

deck: Nephew of Melf, the original Elf with a Gun.
description:
Origin

Created by Steve Gerber, Relf is the nephew of Melf, the original Elf with a Gun, whom Gerber also created. See Time Agent for a different group of Elves with Guns.

Major Story Arcs

Relf appears on Earth and wants revenge on the truck driver who killed Melf. He teams with with the Circus of Crime and is interrupted by Spider-Man. At one point an Officer Dragon shows up with a duck.

Relf, though a Marvel character, also shows up in the Savage Dragon/Destroyer Duck crossover, which fills in more of the same Circus of Crime story.

Powers and Abilities

Relf has various magical powers, including some level of matter manipulation.
name: Relf

deck: Mysterious Elves with Guns who work for the Tribunal, (not to be?) confused with the original Elf with a Gun, Melf, or his nephew, Relf.
description:
Origin

In early issues of The Defenders, Steve Gerber created a cult-classic character known as the Elf with a Gun, later named Melf. On multiple occasions, he appeared and killed a random civilian with no connection to the rest of the storyline. These characters and events were never explained.

Years later, J.M. DeMatteis wrote a storyline to retroactively explain the Elf with a Gun, saying they were Time Agents of a mysterious Tribunal.

However, years after that, Peter David wrote a story (Incredible Hulk 370) in which Dr. Strange called the events in the DeMatteis story a âcosmic hoax,â making the truth about events and the characters of the DeMatteis story now unclear.

Years after that, Gerber wrote a story with another Elf, known as Relf, nephew of the original Melf, who seemed to have no connection to the DeMatteis Time Agent characterizations of the Elves.

Thus the Time Agentsâ self-descriptions may or may not be true (depending on how one interprets Strangeâs very ambiguous comments about the cosmic hoax), but they do seem to be different from the Melf and Relf versions of the Elf with a Gun.

This page is about the DeMatteis Time Agent Elves, who seem to be their own entities. Relf, the original Elf with a Gun, and his nephew, Relf, have their own separate pages.

Major Story Arcs

Luann Bloom, Kyle Richmondâs nurse, thinks the Defenders were involved in his apparent death. She is contacted by a Time Agent Elf, number 334A-W (later named 3217.9), who says he has information on what happened. However, it is a set-up.

Once he gets her in his car, it turns into a Model T Ford and they are suddenly driving in the country instead of New York City. They go into a barn and start traveling to the end of time. There, the Time Agent introduces Bloom to the Tribunal, for whom he works.

The Tribunal is a group of cosmic entities that work as antibodies for the universe, fixing problems as they happen upon them. At one point in the future, they found out that Earth had been destroyed by a strange event around our point in history.

The Tribunal created the Time Agents to investigate what happened. They were modeled off of elves, since they exist in many culturesâ mythologies. The Time Agents, who all look alike, visited many eras before zeroing in on the 1970s and â80s. There, according to the Tribunal, they abducted several individuals with time-displacement guns, which look like human pistols, in an attempt to stop the future calamity. (These are the people who were seemingly killed by Melf in early Defenders issues.) However nothing worked.

They also sent a robot to spy on the Defenders, who they could tell were involved in the future problem. This robot, Luann Bloom, malfunctioned and forgot it was a robot until the Time Agent brought it back to the Tribunal.

They finally realized that the problem centered on the original DefendersâDr. Strange, Silver Surfer, Namor, and Hulk. If they stayed together, they would eventually happen upon an alien ship and accidentally cause the aliens to all commit suicide, including their raceâs prince. The princeâs father, the king of a warrior empire, would later track down the body of his son and destroy the entire Earth in order to properly dispose of the body according to his raceâs traditions.

Once the Time Agents discover the source of the problem, one of them (agent 3217.10) kidnaps the original Defenders before the alien ship lands and brings them to the Tribunal, far in the future. He and his brother then help the Tribunal explain the problem to the Defenders, usually in a fairly caustic manner. Agent 3127.10 also narrates parts of the story directly to the reader, breaking the fourth wall.

Eventually the Defenders agree to break up in order to keep the catastrophe from happening.

However, some years later Dr. Strange tells the other Defenders that he looked into the whole thing later on, and discovered that it was all a cosmic hoax. This was never explained in detail; it is unclear whether the hoax merely involved the story of the crashed alien ship, or whether the Tribunal and/or Time Agents are not even who they said they are. (When they were first taken into the future, Strange did use the Eye of Agamotto to examine the Tribunal. According to the Eye at the time, the Tribunal was who it said it was.)

The Time Agentsâ story is also complex because the people they are said to have abducted are mostly (but not entirely) the same people seemingly killed by the original Elf with a Gun, and in fact the Time Agent/Tribunal storyline was originally written to explain both the Elf with a Gun appearances as well as some shadowy appearances of a mysterious commission that was also never otherwise explained. However, not only was the Time Agents/Tribunal storyline later called a hoax, thus calling into question whether the Time Agents were really the same as the Elf with a Gun (who was named Melf), but the supposed nephew of the Elf with a Gun, named Relf, showed up some time later and seemed to be unconnected to the Time Agents. Therefore it seems that Melf and Relf are not the same kind of Elves as the Time Agents.

The Time Agents are often sarcastic trouble-makers, misogynistic, and cruel. For instance they take joy in harassing Luann Bloom and eventually turning her off. The Tribunal is often impatient with them, threatening to send them back to the gene pool where they would be melted down.

Differences between Melf and the Time Agents

Melf wears green and has red hair and a red goatee. He carries a revolver. The Time Agents wear red and have white hair and goatees. They carry semiautomatic pistols.

Powers and Abilities

The Time Agents are able to travel through time. They do so at least partly through advanced technology from the Tribunal, but may also be able to do so using innate powers.

They have various forms of advanced technology, including time-displacement pistols that can send other people through time without their consent, even powerful beings like Dr. Strange and Silver Surfer.

They also have undefined other strange abilities of a fairly high level. For instance, one Time Agent was able to send a psychic summons to Namor, Hulk, and Surfer, in which he pretended to be Dr. Strange. Even the Surfer was unable to detect that it came from the Time Agent instead of Strange.

They are able to instantly learn a time periodâs languages, history, and culture.

deck: Julianne Quinn was a psychologist who came into conflict with Freddy Krueger.
description:
Biography

Dr. Julianne Quinn was introduced as the apparent protagonist for Marvel's short-lived black and white magazine Freddy Krueger's A Nightmare on Elm Street. Julianne was a Springwood native who had tried to escape the town by becoming a successful psychiatrist. She was a particular expert on dreams, and was a skilled lucid dreamer in her own right, often making herself fly by growing wings in her dreams. She was in contact with a famous dream researcher in Mexico.

Julianne was called to treat a young girl named Allison Hayes who was being targeted by Krueger. Julianne herself was also being targeted by Krueger (Whom he mockingly called "Jools") and tried to prepare by teaching Allison to control her dreams, as well as researching the history of Freddy Krueger and his mother. She attempted to help Allison by giving her the dream suppressant Hypnocil, but came into conflict with the staff of the hospital where she was treating Allison.

She was murdered by Krueger though, and seemingly decided to join forces with him and kill her former patient. She then took on a snake-like form and attacked Allison before apparently being slain again by her former patient. Whether this was all an illusion created by Krueger or she truly joined up with him was never answered since the series was cancelled.

The character seems partially patterned after Nancy Thompson as she is depicted in the third Nightmare on Elm Street film, Dream Warriors. Her bond with Allison before turning evil mirrors the one between Nancy and Kristen Parker. She also prefigures the character of Maggie Burroughs from the sixth film; Freddy's Dead, in many ways. The concept of a former Krueger enemy/victim becoming his accomplice would also turn up in Innovation's Nightmares on Elm Street comics (Where the Dream Warriors are prone to being controlled by Freddy) and in Freddy Vs Jason Vs Ash: The Nightmare Warriors where Maggie Burroughs becomes evil. The scenes of her researching Krueger's past were also the first depiction of the character's origin in any medium.
name: Dr. Julianne Quinn

deck: Allison Hayes aka Dreamstalker, was the heroine of Marvel's short-lived Nightmare on Elm Street magazine.
description:
Biography

Allison Hayes was a teenager being targeted by Freddy Krueger. She was born with extraordinary abilities which made her a "Dreamstalker", with the ability to control her dreams. Ever since she was a little girl, she had had this power, and wandered into different parts of the Dream Dimension. Unfortunately, Dreamstalkers are prone to being easily manipulated by beings who exist in the Dream Dimension and easily fooled into thinking an evil being is a good one.

Allison had no idea of this at first, and when being treated for her nightmares by Dr. Julianne Quinn, demonstrated her abilities when she entered one of Quinn's dreams and saved her from Krueger by taking the form of a living fireball, then a female wrestler. Julianne learned what Allison was after talking to a friend of hers in Mexico who was an expert on dream myths, and planned on warning Allison about her vulnerability, but she was killed by Krueger before she could do this.

Allison reveled in her powers as the Dreamstalker, even spending waking hours drawing new identities she could change into in her dreams. One of them was her dressed in Krueger's own clothes.

Her epic battle with Krueger and a now evil Julianne unfortunately caused her to sleepwalk, and she was woken up and dragged off to solitary. Krueger had also previously been unaware of her powers, but learned of it in this battle. It is unknown if Allison defeated Krueger, or if she succumbed to his influence, as she made several quips when battling him that were similar to ones Krueger had made previously. The third issue was never published.

Film allusions

The character of Allison has similarities with the Nightmare on Elm Street film characters of Kristen Parker from Dream Warriors (Particularly in her artistic abilities and bond with her psychiatrist/mentor) and Alice Johnson ('the Dream Master") from the fourth film Dream Master, and some of her punk-inspired proposed appearances for her Dreamstalker identity resembled Taryn White's "beautiful and bad" alter ego from Dream Warriors. Allison is named after actress Allison Hayes, who appeared in many horror films, notably the titular role in the 1958 camp classic Attack of the 50ft Woman.
name: Dreamstalker

description:
Katja Zukov is an expatriate psychic medium Russian in America. To improve her chances in her field, when Katja was young, her parents moved from Soviet Russia to America, leaving their younger son Mikas behind with a grandmother, with the intention of sending for him at a later date, but soon after arriving in America, the Zukov's died of environmental cancer caused by poisonous fumes they were exposed to in Russia. Mikas was left abandoned and resents that.

Katja, stranded without family in America was placed in an orphanage where she met Assistant District Attorney Ben Feldman, who was so impressed he adopted her to raise alongside his son Jules, who as an adult is still her best friend and business manager.

As a very strong medium, Katja's psychic ability allows the goddess Kaos Moon to enter our reality physically as an astral projection through Katja's mind, but every time she channels the goddess, he body and brain endure terrific stress and damage, which has to be treated by medication. Katja and Jules are concerned about her increasing dependence on the drugs, afraid of addiction or even death from their use.
name: Katja Zukov

description:
Kaos Moon is (probably) a creature of time and space (aka, A GODDESS), who enter our world as an astral projection through the fragile human body of human psychic Katja Zukov. She uses a moon-bladed staff of energy to battle beings of the supranormal in protection of others and the planet (animals, environment, etc).

Every time she phases through Katja's mind and body, she causes damage to her vessel, but to enter our reality, a strong psychic mind is required and humans are not yet evolved enough to withstand the channeling without damage.

As a a result of this damage caused to her body, with every visitation of Kaos Moon, Katja required more medication and becomes more and more dependent, much to her dismay and the concern of her loved ones.

Created by David Boller, the latest appearance of this Goddess have appeared in Avatar Press's Thresholds anthology series. the entire first series, Full Circle, is available at David Boller's website.
name: Kaos Moon

description:
Turned into a bitten werewolf as a young boy, Clayton lived as a feral wolf-boy for several years until Jeremy found and "tamed" him. Surprisingly cerebral, Clayton has at least one doctorate in Anthroplogy.

While guest-lecturing at a university in Toronto, Clayton met and fell in love with Elena Michaels. Deciding he could not live without her, he bit her, making her a werewolf. What followed was 10+ years of fighting as Elena was convinced she hated him. After ten years on her own, though Elena finally realized she did love Clay and they have the only two dual-parented werewolf children.
name: Clayton Danvers

description:
Jeremy Malcolm Edward Danvers was born to be the leader of The Pack (the only pack of werewolves in North America). He took the leadership in 1985 when Dominic Sorrentino died. His abusive father, Malcom Danvers, thought *he* was better suited to lead but soon learned that strong doesn't mean a better leader.

Jeremy raised Clayton Danvers and all the other wolves assumed he was grooming Clay to be his heir as Alpha, but he chose Elena. After retiring early, Jeremy can now spend more time enjoying his time with the twins and spending time on a love life with Necromancer Jaime Vegas.
name: Jeremy Danvers
